\begin_layout Section
overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
moretp is a simple text protocol that allows embedding of binary data.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The TCP byte stream is divided into packets.
 A packet is a line terminated by '
\backslash
n' followed by an optional binary part, representing a list of strings.
 When decoding a packet, lines are processed to remove leading and trailing
 whitespace and all other whitespace sequences are normalized to a single
 ' '.
 After this processing, each line corresponds uniquely to a sequence of
 non-empty, non-whitespace-containing words.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If any word in a line begins with '<', the rest of the word is passed to
 strtoul(3) to get a byte count.
 The total byte count of the words in the line is the length of the binary
 part of the packet.
 To complete decoding of the packet, each word beginning with '<' is replaced
 by the corresponding bytes in the packet's binary part.
 Then the resulting word list is the decoded packet.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To encode a moretp packet, start with a list of a strings.
 An empty list corresponds to the packet "
\backslash
n".
 If none of the strings contain any whitespace, then the packet is the list
 joined by ' ' and terminated by '
\backslash
n'.
 If any string contains whitespace, replace it with '<' followed by its
 length prior to the joining, and append the original string to the final
 packet.
 Or, do this for every string whether or not it contains whitespace.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A moretp encoder in perl.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
sub moretpenc {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
  join(' ', map /
\backslash
s/ ? "<" .
 length : $_, @_) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
  "
\backslash
n" .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
  join('', grep /
\backslash
s/, @_)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
http over moretp
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as the HTTP request line and request headers are not sensitive to
 multiple whitespace, and do not contain any '<' characters, each line can
 be understood as a moretp packet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This is both moretp and HTTP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
GET / HTTP/1.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Host: localhost:9999
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Connection: keep-alive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Upgrade-Insecure-Requests: 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate, br
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim

\end_layout

