\begin_layout Verbatim
To handle binary or whitespace-containing request and response bodies, we
 can use the trick of adding an extra header to encapsulate the body in
 a single moretp packet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This is also valid moretp.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
POST /test HTTP/1.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Host: localhost:9999
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Content-Length: 21
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
Content-Type: text/plain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
X-Moretp-Length: <23
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim

\end_layout

\begin_layout Verbatim
extra  space  between
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way a moretp server can communicate with HTTP clients without any
 special server-side support.
\end_layout

